<subSubSection id="3AE650FBC566FFB9FF3EF9E6B6C2F97A" pageId="1" pageNumber="669" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="72430370C566FFB9FF3EF9E6B6C2F97A" blockId="1.[151,1437,1534,2028]" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C566FFB9FF3EF9E6B424F99E" bold="true" box="[199,334,1606,1632]" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is given in honor of Dr. Jocélia Grazia for her enormous contribution to the knowledge of South American Pentatomomorpha; noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3AE650FBC566FFBBFF3EF92DB434FD33" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="671" pageId="1" pageNumber="669" type="description">
<paragraph id="72430370C566FFB9FF3EF92DB4D8F90F" blockId="1.[151,1437,1534,2028]" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C566FFB9FF3EF92DB433F959" bold="true" box="[199,345,1677,1703]" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">Description.</emphasis>
Female: Measurements (n = 1): Total length: 5.79; width: 2.84. Head. Length: 0.95; width: 1.42; interocular space: 0.93; antennal segment lengths I: 0.32; II: 0.55; III: 0.38; IV: 0.58; V: 0.66. Pronotum. Length: 1.10; width at base: 2.55.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72430370C566FFB9FF3EF95AB023F812" blockId="1.[151,1437,1534,2028]" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">
General coloration shiny dark brown dorsally (
<figureCitation id="EAC71FF5C566FFB9FD18F95AB64FF8EA" box="[737,805,1786,1812]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-156@2.[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hyperbius joceliae n. sp. 1. Dorsal View. 2. Head. 3. Metapleura. 4. Abdomen. 5. Pendergrast’s Organ. 6. Female genitalia. Caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="669">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Apex of anteclypeus and mandibular plates, antennal segments I, II, basal half of III and extreme base of IV, lateral margins of the pronotum and median line to the level of the base of the calli, pale yellowish. Apical half of antennal segment III and ¾ apical of IV, reddish brown. Scutellum dark reddish brown; scutellum, internal margin of the endocorium, and external margin of the exocorium, lighter than the rest, without becoming pale. Ventrally the same color as the dorsum, with the basal half of head whitish, bucculae, rostrum and legs yellowish brown. Membrane translucent, smoked. Dorsal surface with erect, short and very scattered pilosity. Well-marked and densely dispersed punctures on the entire dorsal surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72430370C565FFBAFF3EFF37B7D6FE53" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">
Head (
<figureCitation id="EAC71FF5C565FFBAFEEAFF37B433FF4F" box="[275,345,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-156@2.[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hyperbius joceliae n. sp. 1. Dorsal View. 2. Head. 3. Metapleura. 4. Abdomen. 5. Pendergrast’s Organ. 6. Female genitalia. Caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Wider than long, with subtle punctures and rugosities on the lateral margin of the mandibular plates. The anterior margin of the latter approximately at the same level as the anteclypeus. First antennal segment short, just reaching the apex of the head; second segment very short but longer than the third and sub-equal to the fourth, the fifth segment is the longest. Eyes prominent and externally rounded, with their internal and basal margin straight, with an angular shape. Ocelli rounded, larger than superficial punctures, not contiguous with pronotum. Bucculae very thin; labium arising the posterior coxae; first labial segment short, which does not exceed the posterior margin of the bucculae. The second segment is the longest, third and fourth segments of sub-equal length, these last with long erect hairs on their ventral surface.
</paragraph>
<caption id="268353F8C565FFBAFF6EF822B4D2F840" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="670" startId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" targetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="72430370C565FFBAFF6EF822B4D2F840" blockId="2.[151,1436,1922,1982]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFF6EF822B451F864" bold="true" box="[151,315,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">FIGURES 1–6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="B5FC78F3C565FFBAFEBBF822B768F864" authority="Carpintero &amp; Biase, 2021" authorityName="Carpintero &amp; Biase" authorityYear="2021" box="[322,514,1922,1946]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Hyperbius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="670" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joceliae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFEBBF822B768F864" box="[322,514,1922,1946]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">Hyperbius joceliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFDF0F822B736F864" bold="true" box="[521,604,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="5BBB6219C565FFBAFDF0F822B728F864" box="[521,578,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
1.
</emphasis>
Dorsal View. 
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFD14F822B66AF864" bold="true" box="[749,768,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">2.</emphasis>
Head. 
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFCB0F822B636F864" bold="true" box="[841,860,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">3.</emphasis>
Metapleura. 
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFC1AF822B69CF864" bold="true" box="[995,1014,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">4.</emphasis>
Abdomen. 
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFB95F822B115F864" bold="true" box="[1132,1151,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">5.</emphasis>
Pendergrast’s Organ. 
<emphasis id="4088DF62C565FFBAFA98F822B01EF864" bold="true" box="[1377,1396,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="670">6.</emphasis>
Female genitalia. Caudal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="72430370C564FFBBFF3EFF37B149FDE7" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">
Thorax. Pronotum subquadrangular, more than twice as wide at its base as long, laterally thinned but lacking a true carina. Dorsal surface covered by thick, sparse and dark inside punctures with anterior margin of calli with thinner and more densely arranged punctures; calluses nearly smooth. Scutellum longer than wide, apically thin, with punctures more densely sparse on its apical half; clavus with longitudinal scores in all its extension: three rows at its base, but only one reaching its apex, the inner one; hemelytra very little convex laterally; corium dense and homogeneously punctured; membrane hyaline grayish, smoky and with a few weak longitudinal veins. Sternal region covered with brown punctures, denser on prosternum; meso and metasternum mostly smooth. Scent gland peritreme (
<figureCitation id="EAC71FF5C564FFBBFF59FE33B589FE53" box="[160,227,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-156@2.[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hyperbius joceliae n. sp. 1. Dorsal View. 2. Head. 3. Metapleura. 4. Abdomen. 5. Pendergrast’s Organ. 6. Female genitalia. Caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) large, with a wide opaque evaporatorium, occupying the anterior half of the metapleura and delimited by an irregular groove; this area is continued in the posterior half of the mesopleura, very similar to that present in 
<taxonomicName id="B5FC78F3C564FFBBFA78FE17B472FE0B" authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1863" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Ditomotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="671" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geniculatus">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C564FFBBFA78FE17B472FE0B" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">H. geniculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
showing its shape to be a generic character. Legs with erect silvery pilosity on its inner margin more densely towards its apical half. Second tarsal segment of length equal to the first.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72430370C564FFBBFF3EFD83B434FD33" blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="EAC71FF5C564FFBBFEB1FD83B4E4FDC3" box="[328,398,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-156@2.[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hyperbius joceliae n. sp. 1. Dorsal View. 2. Head. 3. Metapleura. 4. Abdomen. 5. Pendergrast’s Organ. 6. Female genitalia. Caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Sparse but homogeneously punctured throughout. Connexivum of the same color as the rest of the abdomen. Genitalia (
<figureCitation id="EAC71FF5C564FFBBFE03FDE7B755FD9C" box="[506,575,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1922,1946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-156@2.[151,1435,453,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hyperbius joceliae n. sp. 1. Dorsal View. 2. Head. 3. Metapleura. 4. Abdomen. 5. Pendergrast’s Organ. 6. Female genitalia. Caudal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692791" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692791/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). First gonocoxae wider than long, light brown, faintly rough longitudinally; second gonocoxae with each gonocoxite subquadrangular, light brown, with faintly marked transverse roughness; paratergite 9 subtriangular, apically less acute than in 
<taxonomicName id="B5FC78F3C564FFBBFD0FFD2FB6F0FD57" authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1863" box="[758,922,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Ditomotarsus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="671" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geniculatus">
<emphasis id="4088DF62C564FFBBFD0FFD2FB6F0FD57" box="[758,922,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="671">H. geniculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also light brown, only with its apical margin clear and smooth.
</paragraph>
